    <p xml:id="auto_8j19f36o">
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_yscvhm3r">
        A <m>\textbf{clinometer}</m> (or inclinometer) is a tool used to measure the angle of elevation
        (looking up) and the angle of depression (looking down).
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_yytb21om">
        The figure below shows a person standing on the ground, looking at an object at the top. This forms an angle of elevation. 
        When looking down from a higher point, it forms an angle of depression.
    </p>
    <image width="50%">
    <latex-image label="Dippression1">
        \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Ground Line
            \draw[thick] (-1,-0.5) -- (7,-0.5);


            % Observer (Person)
            \draw[thick] (1,0) -- (1,2); % Body
            \draw[thick,fill=cyan] (1,2) circle (0.2); % Head
            \draw[thick] (1,2) -- (0.5,1.5); % Left Arm
            \draw[thick] (1,2) -- (1.5,1.5); % Right Arm
            \draw[thick] (1,0) -- (0.7,-0.5); % Left Leg
            \draw[thick] (1,0) -- (1.3,-0.5); % Right Leg

            % Eye Level Line
            \draw[dashed] (1,2) -- (7,2);

            % Angles of Elevation and Depression
            \draw[very thick] (1,2) -- (6,4.5); % Angle of Elevation
            \draw[very thick] (1,2) -- (6,0.5); % Angle of Depression

            % Labels for Angles
            \path (3.5,2) ++(15:1.5) node { Angle of elevation};
            \path (3.5,2) ++(-15:1.5) node { Angle of depression};

            % Objects at higher and lower positions
            \draw[thick] (6,4.5) rectangle (7.5,4.9);
            \draw[thick] (6,0.5) rectangle (7.5,0.9);

            % Labels for Objects
            \node at (6.7,4.65) {\(\mathbf{Object}\)};
            \node at (6.7,0.65) {\(\mathbf{Object}\)};

            % Indicating angles
            \draw[very thick] (1.8,2) arc[start angle=0, end angle=25, radius=0.8];
            \draw[very thick] (1.8,2) arc[start angle=0, end angle=-25, radius=0.8];

            % Angle Labels
            \node [right]at (2.3,2.35) {$\theta_1$};
            \node[right] at (2.3,1.65) {$\theta_2$};
            \node[below] at (7,0) {Ground};
        \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
        
        
    </image>
    <p xml:id="auto_qusnz2j5">
        The dashed line is the horizontal line.
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_sznz6n4b">
        <ul xml:id="auto_6rb3o64m">
            <li xml:id="auto_4h6y2k5v">
                <p xml:id="auto_w4dv0svt">
                    <m>\textbf{Angle of Elevation:}</m>  The angle measured upward from a horizontal line to an object above.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_t2tmwvvp">
                <p xml:id="auto_6uzhfslt">
                    <m>\textbf{Angle of Depression:}</m> The angle measured downward from a horizontal line to an object below.
                </p>

                
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    

    


    <example xml:id="auto_d4pubc7c">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_8xkc296i">
                A person stands <m>20\,\text{m}</m> away from a tree. The angle of elevation from their eyes (<m>1.6\,\text{m}</m> above the ground) to the top of the tree is <m>35^\circ</m>. Find the height of the tree.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_q88asss8">
                Consider the sketch below:
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="elevation-tree-example"> 
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Using polar coordinates for exact 35° angle
                    % Eye position at origin for angle calculation
                    \coordinate (eye) at (0,0.8);
                    % Line of sight at 35° for 6 units horizontal distance
                    % At 35°, to reach x=6: distance = 6/cos(35°) = 7.32
                    \coordinate (treetop) at ($(eye) + (35:7.32)$);
                    % Ground line
                    \draw[very thick] (-0.5,0) -- (6.5,0);
                    % Tree at x=6
                    \pgfmathsetmacro{\treeheight}{0.8 + 6*tan(35)}
                    \draw[very thick, green!50!brown] (6,0) -- (6,\treeheight);
                    \fill[green!30] (6,\treeheight) -- (5.5,\treeheight-0.7) -- (6,\treeheight-0.5) -- (6.5,\treeheight-0.7) -- cycle;
                    \node[above] at (6,\treeheight+0.1) {Tree};
                    % Person (eye level at 0.8 units representing 1.6m)
                    \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (eye);
                    \draw[thick,fill=cyan] (eye) circle (0.15);
                    % Eye level line
                    \draw[dashed, thin] (eye) -- (6,0.8);
                    % Line of sight using polar direction
                    \draw[very thick, dashed, blue] (eye) -- (6,\treeheight);
                    % Angle of elevation - exactly 35°
                    \draw ($(eye) + (0:0.8)$) arc[start angle=0, end angle=35, radius=0.8cm];
                    \node at ($(eye) + (17.5:1.2)$) {$35^\circ$};
                    % Right angle mark
                    \draw (5.7,0.8) -- (5.7,1.1) -- (6,1.1);
                    % Labels
                    \node[below] at (3,0) {$20\,\text{m}$};
                    \node[left] at (0,0.4) {$1.6\,\text{m}$};
                    \node[right] at (6,2.9) {$h$};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
                
                
            </image>
            <p xml:id="auto_o4lvvof0">
                Use <m>\tan\,\theta</m>:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_c68wke40">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \tan\,35^\circ \amp = \frac{h}{20} </mrow>
                    <mrow> h \amp = 20 \times \tan\,35^\circ </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = 20 \times 0.7002 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = 14.00\,\text{m} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Total height of tree = <m>h + 1.6 = 14.00 + 1.6 = 15.6\,\text{m}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_pj4nxme3">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_tieznjxk">
                A lighthouse is <m>50\,\text{m}</m> tall. A sailor spots the top of the lighthouse at an angle of elevation of <m>25^\circ</m>.
                How far is the ship from the base of the lighthouse? 
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_yuq45rcj">
                Consider the sketch below:
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="elevation-lighthouse-example">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Using polar coordinates for exact 25° angle
                    % Ship/observer at origin
                    \coordinate (ship) at (0,0);
                    % Lighthouse height = 3 units, so horizontal = 3/tan(25°)
                    \pgfmathsetmacro{\lhdist}{3/tan(25)}
                    % Water/ground line
                    \draw[very thick] (-0.5,0) -- (7,0);
                    \fill[blue!20] (-0.5,-0.3) rectangle (2,0);
                    % Lighthouse at calculated distance
                    \draw[very thick, gray] (\lhdist,0) -- (\lhdist,3);
                    \fill[gray!30] (\lhdist-0.15,0) rectangle (\lhdist+0.15,3);
                    \draw[thick, yellow, fill=yellow!50] (\lhdist-0.3,3) -- (\lhdist,3.4) -- (\lhdist+0.3,3) -- cycle;
                    \node[above] at (\lhdist,3.5) {Lighthouse};
                    % Ship at origin
                    \draw[thick, brown] (0.3,0) -- (0,0.3) -- (0.6,0.3) -- (0.3,0);
                    \draw[thick, brown] (0.3,0.3) -- (0.3,0.6);
                    \node[below] at (0.3,-0.1) {Ship};
                    % Line of sight using polar: from origin at 25° angle
                    \draw[very thick, dashed, blue] (ship) -- ($(ship) + (25:7)$);
                    % Angle of elevation - exactly 25°
                    \draw ($(ship) + (0:0.8)$) arc[start angle=0, end angle=25, radius=0.8cm];
                    \node at ($(ship) + (12.5:1.3)$) {$25^\circ$};
                    % Right angle mark
                    \draw (\lhdist-0.3,0) -- (\lhdist-0.3,0.3) -- (\lhdist,0.3);
                    % Labels
                    \node[below] at (3.2,0) {$d = ?$};
                    \node[right] at (\lhdist+0.2,1.5) {$50\,\text{m}$};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
                
            </image>
            <p xml:id="auto_c9c3alkn">
                Use <m>\tan</m>:
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_eze40rk5">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \tan\,25^\circ \amp = \frac{50}{d} </mrow>
                    <mrow> d \amp = \frac{50}{\tan\,25^\circ} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \frac{50}{0.4663} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = 107.2\,\text{m}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    
    <exercises xml:id="auto_gdobvxst" >

            <exercise xml:id="auto_6jln7a5k">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_xhxr6ct4">
                    If the angle of elevation is <m>30^\circ</m> and the horizontal distance to the object is <m>50\,\text{m}</m>,
                    find the height above eye level.
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="exercise-elevation-30">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Ground/horizontal line
                        \draw[very thick] (0,0) -- (5,0);
                        % Vertical height
                        \draw[very thick] (5,0) -- (5,2.89);
                        % Line of sight
                        \draw[very thick, dashed, blue] (0,0) -- (5,2.89);
                        % Right angle mark
                        \draw (4.7,0) -- (4.7,0.3) -- (5,0.3);
                        % Angle of elevation
                        \draw (1,0) arc[start angle=0, end angle=30, radius=1cm];
                        \node at (1.4,0.3) {$30^\circ$};
                        % Labels
                        \node[below] at (2.5,0) {$50\,\text{m}$};
                        \node[right] at (5,1.4) {$h = ?$};
                        \node[left] at (0,0) {Eye level};
                        \node[above] at (5,2.89) {Object};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    In this problem:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Horizontal distance (adjacent) = <m>50\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>Angle of elevation = <m>30^\circ</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>Height above eye level (opposite) = <m>h</m></p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Using tangent (opposite over adjacent):
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\tan\,30^\circ \amp = \frac{h}{50}</mrow>
                        <mrow>h \amp = 50 \times \tan\,30^\circ</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 50 \times 0.5774</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 28.87\,\text{m}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The height above eye level is approximately <m>28.9\,\text{m}</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

            <exercise xml:id="ex-giraffe-elevation">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A wildlife photographer in the Maasai Mara stands <m>25\,\text{m}</m> away from a giraffe. 
                    The angle of elevation from the photographer's eye level (<m>1.7\,\text{m}</m> above ground) 
                    to the top of the giraffe's head is <m>12^\circ</m>. Calculate the total height of the giraffe.
                </p>
                <image width="65%">
                <latex-image label="exercise-giraffe">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Ground line (savanna)
                        \draw[very thick, yellow!70!brown] (-0.5,0) -- (8.5,0);
                        \fill[yellow!30!green, opacity=0.3] (-0.5,0) rectangle (8.5,-0.2);
                        
                        % Define key points using polar coordinates for accurate 12 degree angle
                        % Scale: 1 unit = 4.167m, so 25m = 6 units, 1.7m = 0.408 units
                        % Eye level height: 1.7m = 0.408 units (scaled)
                        \def\eyeHeight{0.408}
                        % Horizontal distance: 25m = 6 units
                        \def\horizDist{6}
                        % Height above eye level: 25 * tan(12) = 5.315m = 1.276 units
                        % Total giraffe height: 1.7 + 5.315 = 7.015m = 1.684 units
                        \def\giraffeTopHeight{1.684}
                        
                        \coordinate (eyeLevel) at (0,\eyeHeight);
                        \coordinate (giraffeTop) at ({\horizDist}, \giraffeTopHeight);
                        
                        % Cartoon Giraffe centered at x=6, to scale
                        % Total height = 1.684 units from ground to top of horns
                        % Legs (about 25% of height)
                        \draw[very thick, orange!80!brown] (5.7,0) -- (5.7,0.42);
                        \draw[very thick, orange!80!brown] (5.9,0) -- (5.9,0.42);
                        \draw[very thick, orange!80!brown] (6.3,0) -- (6.3,0.42);
                        \draw[very thick, orange!80!brown] (6.5,0) -- (6.5,0.42);
                        % Body (ellipse, about 15% of height)
                        \fill[orange!70!yellow] (6.1,0.55) ellipse (0.55cm and 0.2cm);
                        % Spots on body
                        \fill[orange!50!brown] (5.85,0.55) circle (0.06);
                        \fill[orange!50!brown] (6.1,0.6) circle (0.05);
                        \fill[orange!50!brown] (6.35,0.52) circle (0.055);
                        % Neck - long giraffe neck (about 50% of height)
                        \fill[orange!70!yellow] (5.85,0.65) -- (5.75,1.45) -- (6.0,1.45) -- (6.05,0.65) -- cycle;
                        % Spots on neck
                        \fill[orange!50!brown] (5.88,0.8) circle (0.04);
                        \fill[orange!50!brown] (5.9,1.0) circle (0.045);
                        \fill[orange!50!brown] (5.87,1.2) circle (0.04);
                        \fill[orange!50!brown] (5.92,1.35) circle (0.035);
                        % Head - positioned at correct height
                        \fill[orange!70!yellow] (5.87,1.52) ellipse (0.15cm and 0.1cm);
                        % Ears
                        \fill[orange!70!yellow] (5.75,1.58) -- (5.68,1.68) -- (5.78,1.6) -- cycle;
                        \fill[orange!70!yellow] (6.0,1.58) -- (6.07,1.68) -- (5.97,1.6) -- cycle;
                        % Ossicones (horns) - top of giraffe at giraffeTopHeight
                        \draw[thick, orange!60!brown] (5.8,1.6) -- (5.78,1.684);
                        \fill[orange!40!brown] (5.78,1.684) circle (0.03);
                        \draw[thick, orange!60!brown] (5.95,1.6) -- (5.97,1.684);
                        \fill[orange!40!brown] (5.97,1.684) circle (0.03);
                        % Eye
                        \fill[black] (5.78,1.53) circle (0.02);
                        % Snout
                        \fill[orange!60!yellow] (5.72,1.5) ellipse (0.06cm and 0.04cm);
                        % Tail
                        \draw[thick, orange!60!brown] (6.65,0.6) .. controls (6.75,0.7) and (6.8,0.5) .. (6.75,0.4);
                        \fill[orange!40!brown] (6.75,0.37) ellipse (0.04cm and 0.07cm);
                        
                        % Photographer (person icon) - scaled to 1.7m = 0.408 units
                        \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (0,0.3);
                        \draw[thick,fill=cyan] (0,0.36) circle (0.07);
                        \node[below] at (0,-0.15) {\small Photographer};
                        % Camera at eye level
                        \draw[thick, black, fill=gray] (-0.08,0.25) rectangle (0.08,0.32);
                        
                        % Eye level dashed line (horizontal reference)
                        \draw[dashed, thin, gray] (0,\eyeHeight) -- (6,\eyeHeight);
                        
                        % Line of sight to top of giraffe using polar coordinates for exact 12 degree angle
                        \draw[very thick, dashed, blue] (eyeLevel) -- (giraffeTop);
                        
                        % Vertical line from eye level to giraffe top
                        \draw[thick, gray] ({\horizDist}, \eyeHeight) -- ({\horizDist}, \giraffeTopHeight);
                        
                        % Angle of elevation arc - using proper 12 degrees
                        \draw[thick, red] (0,\eyeHeight) ++(0:1.5cm) arc[start angle=0, end angle=12, radius=1.5cm];
                        \node[red] at (2.0,1.0) {$12^\circ$};
                        
                        % Right angle marker at base of triangle
                        \draw[thick] ({\horizDist-0.12}, \eyeHeight) -- ({\horizDist-0.12}, {\eyeHeight+0.12}) -- ({\horizDist}, {\eyeHeight+0.12});
                        
                        % Height marker (h above eye level)
                        \draw[thick, &lt;-&gt;] (7.0,\eyeHeight) -- (7.0,\giraffeTopHeight);
                        \node[right] at (7.0,{0.5*(\eyeHeight+\giraffeTopHeight)}) {$h$};
                        
                        % Total height marker
                        \draw[thick, &lt;-&gt;] (7.6,0) -- (7.6,\giraffeTopHeight);
                        \node[right] at (7.6,{0.5*\giraffeTopHeight}) {\small Total};
                        
                        % Distance label
                        \node[below] at (3,0) {$25\,\text{m}$};
                        \node[left] at (-0.1,0.2) {\small $1.7\,\text{m}$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Given:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Horizontal distance = <m>25\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>Angle of elevation = <m>12^\circ</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>Photographer's eye level = <m>1.7\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p>
                    First, find the height above eye level:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\tan\,12^\circ \amp = \frac{h}{25}</mrow>
                        <mrow>h \amp = 25 \times \tan\,12^\circ</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 25 \times 0.2126</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 5.31\,\text{m}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Total height of giraffe = height above eye level + eye level height:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Total height} \amp = 5.31 + 1.7</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 7.01\,\text{m}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The giraffe is approximately <m>7\,\text{m}</m> tall.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

            <exercise xml:id="auto_tkvrn33m">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_9vfob78u">
                    A surveyor is standing <m>50\,\text{m}</m> away from the base of a mountain. The
                    angle of elevation to the peak of the mountain is <m>30^\circ</m>. Calculate the height of
                    the mountain above the surveyor's eye level.
                </p>
                <image width="55%">
                <latex-image label="exercise-surveyor-mountain">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Using polar coordinates for exact 30° angle
                        \coordinate (eye) at (0,0);
                        % Peak height = 5*tan(30°) at horizontal distance 5
                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\peakheight}{5*tan(30)}
                        % Ground line
                        \draw[very thick] (-0.5,0) -- (5.5,0);
                        % Mountain - peak at calculated height
                        \draw[very thick, brown] (5,0) -- (5,\peakheight);
                        \fill[brown!30] (5,0) -- (5,\peakheight) -- (5.5,\peakheight-0.4) -- (5.3,0) -- cycle;
                        % Surveyor at ground level
                        \draw[thick] (0,-0.3) -- (eye);
                        \draw[thick,fill=cyan] (eye) circle (0.12);
                        % Eye level line
                        \draw[dashed, thin] (eye) -- (5,0);
                        % Line of sight using polar direction - exactly 30°
                        \draw[very thick, dashed, blue] (eye) -- ($(eye) + (30:5.77)$);
                        % Right angle mark
                        \draw (4.7,0) -- (4.7,0.3) -- (5,0.3);
                        % Angle of elevation - exactly 30°
                        \draw ($(eye) + (0:1)$) arc[start angle=0, end angle=30, radius=1cm];
                        \node at ($(eye) + (15:1.5)$) {$30^\circ$};
                        % Labels
                        \node[below] at (0,-0.4) {Surveyor};
                        \node[above] at (5,\peakheight) {Peak};
                        \node[below] at (2.5,-0.1) {$50\,\text{m}$};
                        \node[right] at (5.1,1.5) {$h = ?$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Given:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Horizontal distance (adjacent) = <m>50\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>Angle of elevation = <m>30^\circ</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>Height above eye level (opposite) = <m>h</m></p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Using tangent:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\tan\,30^\circ \amp = \frac{h}{50}</mrow>
                        <mrow>h \amp = 50 \times \tan\,30^\circ</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 50 \times 0.5774</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 28.87\,\text{m}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The height of the mountain above the surveyor's eye level is approximately <m>28.9\,\text{m}</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

            <exercise xml:id="ex-kite-flying">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A student is flying a kite at a school field day. The string is <m>65\,\text{m}</m> long
                    and makes an angle of elevation of <m>52^\circ</m> with the ground. The student holds
                    the string <m>1.2\,\text{m}</m> above the ground. How high is the kite flying above the ground?
                </p>
                <image width="55%">
                <latex-image label="exercise-kite">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Using polar coordinates for exact 52° angle
                        \coordinate (hand) at (0,0.3);
                        % String length = 4 units at 52° angle
                        \coordinate (kite) at ($(hand) + (52:4)$);
                        % Ground line
                        \draw[very thick] (-0.5,0) -- (3.5,0);
                        % Student (hand at 0.3 units representing 1.2m)
                        \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (hand);
                        \draw[thick,fill=cyan] (hand) circle (0.1);
                        \node[below] at (0,-0.1) {Student};
                        % Kite string using polar coordinates - exactly 52°
                        \draw[very thick, blue] (hand) -- (kite);
                        % Kite
                        \draw[thick, red, fill=red!30] (kite) -- ++(0.2,0.4) -- ++(0.2,-0.4) -- ++(-0.2,0.15) -- cycle;
                        \node[above right] at ($(kite) + (0.2,0.4)$) {Kite};
                        % Vertical line (height above hand) - get x-coordinate of kite
                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\kitex}{4*cos(52)}
                        \draw[dashed] (\kitex,0.3) -- (kite);
                        % Horizontal from hand
                        \draw[dashed, thin] (hand) -- (\kitex,0.3);
                        % Angle - exactly 52°
                        \draw ($(hand) + (0:0.7)$) arc[start angle=0, end angle=52, radius=0.7cm];
                        \node at ($(hand) + (26:1.1)$) {$52^\circ$};
                        % Labels
                        \node[above left] at ($(hand) + (52:2)$) {$65\,\text{m}$};
                        \node[right] at ($(kite) + (-0.3,-1.2)$) {$h = ?$};
                        \node[left] at (0,0.15) {$1.2\,\text{m}$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Given:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>String length (hypotenuse) = <m>65\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>Angle of elevation = <m>52^\circ</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>Height of hand above ground = <m>1.2\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Using sine to find the vertical component of the string:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\sin\,52^\circ \amp = \frac{h}{65}</mrow>
                        <mrow>h \amp = 65 \times \sin\,52^\circ</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 65 \times 0.7880</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 51.22\,\text{m}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Total height above ground = vertical component + hand height:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Total height} \amp = 51.22 + 1.2</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 52.42\,\text{m}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The kite is flying approximately <m>52.4\,\text{m}</m> above the ground.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-nairobi-tower">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A tourist standing <m>60\,\text{m}</m> from the base of the Kenyatta International 
                    Convention Centre (KICC) in Nairobi looks up at the top of the tower. The angle 
                    of elevation from her eye level (<m>1.5\,\text{m}</m> above the ground) is <m>60^\circ</m>. 
                    Calculate the height of the KICC tower.
                </p>
                <image width="55%">
                <latex-image label="exercise-kicc-tower">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Using polar coordinates for exact 60° angle
                        \coordinate (eye) at (0,0);
                        % Tower height = 2.5*tan(60°) at horizontal distance 2.5
                        \pgfmathsetmacro{\towerheight}{2.5*tan(60)}
                        % Ground line
                        \draw[very thick] (-0.5,0) -- (3,0);
                        % KICC Tower at x=2.5
                        \draw[very thick, gray] (2.5,0) -- (2.5,\towerheight);
                        \draw[thick, gray] (2.3,\towerheight) -- (2.7,\towerheight);
                        \draw[thick, gray] (2.5,\towerheight) -- (2.5,\towerheight+0.25);
                        \fill[gray!30] (2.35,0) rectangle (2.65,\towerheight);
                        \node[right] at (2.7,\towerheight+0.15) {KICC};
                        % Tourist (eye level at origin)
                        \draw[thick] (0,-0.2) -- (eye);
                        \draw[thick,fill=cyan] (eye) circle (0.1);
                        \node[below] at (0,-0.3) {Tourist};
                        % Eye level line
                        \draw[dashed, thin] (eye) -- (2.5,0);
                        % Line of sight using polar direction - exactly 60°
                        \draw[very thick, dashed, blue] (eye) -- ($(eye) + (60:5)$);
                        % Angle of elevation - exactly 60°
                        \draw ($(eye) + (0:0.5)$) arc[start angle=0, end angle=60, radius=0.5cm];
                        \node at ($(eye) + (30:0.85)$) {$60^\circ$};
                        % Labels
                        \node[below] at (1.25,0) {$60\,\text{m}$};
                        \node[right] at (2.5,2.2) {$h = ?$};
                        \node[left] at (0,-0.1) {$1.5\,\text{m}$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Given:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Horizontal distance = <m>60\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>Angle of elevation = <m>60^\circ</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>Eye level height = <m>1.5\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p>
                    First, find the height above eye level using tangent:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\tan\,60^\circ \amp = \frac{h}{60}</mrow>
                        <mrow>h \amp = 60 \times \tan\,60^\circ</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 60 \times 1.732</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 103.92\,\text{m}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Total height of KICC = height above eye level + eye level:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Total height} \amp = 103.92 + 1.5</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp \approx 105\,\text{m}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The KICC tower is approximately <m>105\,\text{m}</m> tall.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-tree-angle-elevation">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A student stands <m>15\,\text{m}</m> away from a tree. The tree is <m>12\,\text{m}</m> tall, 
                    and the student's eye level is <m>1.5\,\text{m}</m> above the ground. Find the angle of 
                    elevation from the student's eyes to the top of the tree.
                </p>
                <image width="55%">
                <latex-image label="exercise-tree-angle">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Positions
                        \coordinate (eye) at (0,0.75);
                        \coordinate (treetop) at (6,6);
                        % Ground line
                        \draw[very thick] (-0.5,0) -- (6.5,0);
                        % Tree
                        \draw[very thick, green!50!brown] (6,0) -- (6,6);
                        \fill[green!40] (6,6) -- (5.4,5) -- (6,5.3) -- (6.6,5) -- cycle;
                        \node[above] at (6,6.1) {Tree};
                        % Student
                        \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (0,0.5);
                        \draw[thick,fill=cyan] (eye) circle (0.12);
                        \node[below] at (0,-0.1) {Student};
                        % Eye level line
                        \draw[dashed, thin] (eye) -- (6,0.75);
                        % Line of sight to tree top
                        \draw[very thick, dashed, blue] (eye) -- (treetop);
                        % Angle of elevation
                        \draw ($(eye) + (0:1)$) arc[start angle=0, end angle=41, radius=1cm];
                        \node at ($(eye) + (20:1.5)$) {$\theta = ?$};
                        % Right angle mark
                        \draw (5.7,0.75) -- (5.7,1.05) -- (6,1.05);
                        % Labels
                        \node[below] at (3,0) {$15\,\text{m}$};
                        \node[right] at (6.1,3.4) {$12\,\text{m}$};
                        \node[left] at (0,0.35) {$1.5\,\text{m}$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Given:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Tree height = <m>12\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>Eye level = <m>1.5\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>Height above eye level (opposite) = <m>12 - 1.5 = 10.5\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>Horizontal distance (adjacent) = <m>15\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Using tangent:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\tan\,\theta \amp = \frac{10.5}{15}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\tan\,\theta \amp = 0.7</mrow>
                        <mrow>\theta \amp = \tan^{-1}(0.7)</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 34.99^\circ</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The angle of elevation is approximately <m>35^\circ</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-flagpole-angle-elevation">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    During a school assembly, a student stands <m>20\,\text{m}</m> from a flagpole. 
                    The flagpole is <m>18\,\text{m}</m> tall. If the student's eye level is 
                    <m>1.6\,\text{m}</m> above the ground, at what angle of elevation does 
                    she look at the top of the flagpole?
                </p>
                <image width="55%">
                <latex-image label="exercise-flagpole-angle">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Positions
                        \coordinate (eye) at (0,0.5);
                        \coordinate (flagtop) at (5,5.6);
                        % Ground line
                        \draw[very thick] (-0.5,0) -- (5.5,0);
                        % Flagpole
                        \draw[very thick, gray] (5,0) -- (flagtop);
                        \draw[thick, red, fill=red] (5,5.6) -- (5.5,5.3) -- (5,5) -- cycle;
                        \node[above right] at (5.5,5.3) {Flag};
                        % Student
                        \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (0,0.35);
                        \draw[thick,fill=cyan] (eye) circle (0.1);
                        \node[below] at (0,-0.1) {Student};
                        % Eye level line
                        \draw[dashed, thin] (eye) -- (5,0.5);
                        % Line of sight to flag top
                        \draw[very thick, dashed, blue] (eye) -- (flagtop);
                        % Angle of elevation
                        \draw ($(eye) + (0:0.8)$) arc[start angle=0, end angle=46, radius=0.8cm];
                        \node at ($(eye) + (23:1.3)$) {$\theta = ?$};
                        % Right angle mark
                        \draw (4.7,0.5) -- (4.7,0.8) -- (5,0.8);
                        % Labels
                        \node[below] at (2.5,0) {$20\,\text{m}$};
                        \node[right] at (5.1,2.8) {$18\,\text{m}$};
                        \node[left] at (0,0.25) {$1.6\,\text{m}$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Given:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Flagpole height = <m>18\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>Eye level = <m>1.6\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>Height above eye level (opposite) = <m>18 - 1.6 = 16.4\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>Horizontal distance (adjacent) = <m>20\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Using tangent:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\tan\,\theta \amp = \frac{16.4}{20}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\tan\,\theta \amp = 0.82</mrow>
                        <mrow>\theta \amp = \tan^{-1}(0.82)</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 39.35^\circ</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The angle of elevation is approximately <m>39.4^\circ</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-balloon-angle-elevation">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A hot air balloon is tethered to the ground by a rope that is <m>150\,\text{m}</m> long. 
                    The balloon floats directly above a point that is <m>90\,\text{m}</m> from where the 
                    rope is anchored. Find the angle of elevation from the anchor point to the balloon.
                </p>
                <image width="55%">
                <latex-image label="exercise-balloon-angle">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Calculate balloon height using Pythagoras
                        % h = sqrt(150^2 - 90^2) = sqrt(22500 - 8100) = sqrt(14400) = 120
                        % Scale: 150m -> 5 units, so 90m -> 3 units, 120m -> 4 units
                        \coordinate (anchor) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (balloon) at (3,4);
                        % Ground line
                        \draw[very thick] (-0.5,0) -- (4,0);
                        % Vertical line from ground to balloon
                        \draw[dashed, thin] (3,0) -- (balloon);
                        % Rope (hypotenuse)
                        \draw[very thick, brown] (anchor) -- (balloon);
                        % Balloon
                        \draw[thick, red, fill=red!30] (balloon) ellipse (0.4 and 0.5);
                        \draw[thick] (2.7,3.6) -- (3,3.5);
                        \draw[thick] (3.3,3.6) -- (3,3.5);
                        \node[above] at (3,4.6) {Balloon};
                        % Anchor point
                        \fill[black] (anchor) circle (0.1);
                        \node[below] at (0,-0.1) {Anchor};
                        % Angle of elevation
                        \draw ($(anchor) + (0:1)$) arc[start angle=0, end angle=53, radius=1cm];
                        \node at ($(anchor) + (26.5:1.5)$) {$\theta = ?$};
                        % Right angle mark
                        \draw (2.7,0) -- (2.7,0.3) -- (3,0.3);
                        % Labels
                        \node[above left] at (1.5,2) {$150\,\text{m}$};
                        \node[below] at (1.5,0) {$90\,\text{m}$};
                        \node[right] at (3.1,2) {$h$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Given:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Rope length (hypotenuse) = <m>150\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>Horizontal distance (adjacent) = <m>90\,\text{m}</m></p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Using cosine:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\cos\,\theta \amp = \frac{90}{150}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\cos\,\theta \amp = 0.6</mrow>
                        <mrow>\theta \amp = \cos^{-1}(0.6)</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 53.13^\circ</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The angle of elevation from the anchor point to the balloon is approximately <m>53.1^\circ</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    
    </exercises>




